snippet.textDisplay:
Actually, I find weird borders a bit interesting, at least pre Schengen, when they seem to raise all kinds of questions about how they're administered, especially if the countries come into conflict or at least poor relations. What happens to you if you're living in a one house exclave surrounded by a country that yours is now at war with, or dispute with? Even if you're not treated as a potential spy or sent to an internment camp, what about simple things like permitting?

Did this river-wide border allow citizens of either country to boat along it (without having to stay one side of a centerline) I'm musing, or neither without special permit (to make it easier for each side's border guards to monitor) I could imagine in distrustful times?

Technically, committing a crime on that bridge should land you with punishments from both countries, cause you committed a crime in 2 countries, not one. Yes, it was just done in one sitting, but it's still crime in 2 countries so crime twice.


But, I mean, if you think that's harsh, maybe we could just average the punishment between the two countries? But then you have to ask which country's prison the criminal is going.

snippet.textDisplay:
Tom Scott: Huh, that's weird
Jay Foreman: Hey, I can make a fun video out of this! Ahem... So what do you do when you you have a bridge that crosses a border? Well, you could fight over it...
[cue scene of JF and Mark Cooper-Jones in costume]
JF: It's MY bridge
MCJ: No, it's MINE
[back]
MCJ: Or you could agree on an arbitrarily making the border in the middle of the bridge...
[cue scene of JF and MCJ with measuring tapes, making sure they have the exact centre]
JF: Or you could do what the Germans and Belgians did, and share it.
[cue scene of Mosel river]
JF: (in French accent) Wha don't we sharr zis bridge?
MCJ: (in German accent) Ya, das ist gut!


And I'll stop there. Sorry Jay, I'm not writing your damn scripts for you mate!

snippet.textDisplay: Growing up inside the shengen area, I had to educate myself to what a border really means when I wanted to travel abroad. The whole world has been running with them since time immemorial, and here I was trying to grasp some strange concept that had never applied to me before. It's truly a marvel, and I think a lot of the EU citizens have forgotten what it means.
